# Fluff Date: 2026-03-07 18:39:14
<overview>
<p>The Missile Gun Emplacement provides fixed defensive positions with long-range indirect fire capability through standardized Long Range Missile systems. These emplacements serve a fundamentally different tactical role than their direct-fire counterparts, engaging targets at extreme ranges and behind cover without requiring line of sight when paired with forward observers or sensor networks. Their ability to saturate an area with explosive warheads makes them effective against both armored and soft targets.</p><p>Missile emplacements form a critical layer in comprehensive defensive architectures, providing the volume of fire needed to disrupt attacking formations before they can close with direct-fire positions. The combination of LRM batteries with machine gun close defense creates positions that contribute to the battle at every phase, from long-range harassment through final protective fires against infantry assault.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The Medium Missile Gun Emplacement mounts a single LRM 5 and machine gun behind medium armor protection. The improved construction over the light variant allows this emplacement to absorb more punishment before its weapons are compromised, making it suitable for positions closer to the main defensive line where counter-battery fire is more likely. The LRM 5 provides consistent indirect fire support at ranges up to 630 meters.</p><p>Medium armor represents a meaningful improvement in crew survivability compared to light construction. The external power requirement ties the position to existing infrastructure but keeps costs manageable for mass deployment along defensive perimeters. The machine gun deters infantry assault, which remains the most common method of neutralizing fixed missile positions. This variant balances protection, firepower, and economy in proportions suitable for general defensive deployment.</p>
</capabilities>

<history>
<p>The inclusion of missile emplacements within Castle Brian defensive doctrine reflected the Star League Defense Force's understanding that successful fortification required layered defense in depth. The great Castles Brian were not single structures but sprawling complexes covering dozens of square kilometers, and the open ground between defensive rings needed to be covered by weapons that could reach beyond direct line of sight. Long Range Missile batteries filled this role, raining ordnance on approaching forces as they navigated the killing fields between successive defensive lines.</p><p>Castle Brian doctrine called for missile emplacements to be positioned in defilade where possible, protected by terrain features and covered by direct-fire positions that could engage anyone attempting to assault the missile sites directly. Forward observers in hardened bunkers or expendable sensor drones provided targeting data, allowing the missile crews to engage targets they could not see. This combination of indirect fire and protected positioning made missile emplacements among the most difficult components of a Castle Brian to neutralize, as attackers could not simply close range and overwhelm them with superior direct firepower.</p>
</history>

